      <head>Lauterbach &amp; Kuhn</head>

      <div>
        <p>German music publisher, founded 1902,
          purchased by Bote &amp; Bock in 1908. From the first, it was associated with Max
          Reger, one of whose principal publishers it was. It began posthumous publication of works
          of Hugo Wolf in 1903, including small-orchestra and piano-duet arrangements of the 
            <title level="m">Italian Serenade</title>, a piano-duet arrangements of the opera 
            <title level="m">Penthesilea</title> and twelve of the <title level="m">MÃ¶rike
            Lieder</title>, and choral arrangements of six of the <title level="m">Geistliche
          Lieder</title>, all made by Reger. The company used distinctive Jugendstil title-pages and
          outerwrappers (which would have been uncongenial to Schenker).</p>
      </div>
